                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p/>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p> Early provenance unknwon. According to the note on <locus from="2r" to="2r" scheme="folios"/> bought in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100201">Padua</placeName> in <date when="1590"/> by <persName>Hans Poulsen Resen</persName> (1561-1638), Danish bishop and theologian, during his visit to Padua 1589-1591, cf. <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107132">Kornerup (1928–1968)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="1" to="1" unit="volume"/>
                                    <citedRange from="119" to="119" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p> According to a handwritten note at the National Library the manuscript was probably sold by the owners son <persName>Peder Hansen Resen</persName> to <persName>Jörgen Seefeldt</persName> (1594-1662), Danish book collector. The greater part of his library was taken as spoils of war by <persName>Corfitz Ulfeld</persName> (1606-64) in <date when="1658">1658.</date> The manuscript was possibly bequeathed to <persName>Peter Julius Coyet</persName> (1618-67), Swedish diplomat, together with some other books belonging to J. Seefeldt, and then sold at auction in <date from="1700" to="1701">1700–1</date>, cf. <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107131">Walde (1916–1920)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="2" to="2" unit="volume"/>
                                    <citedRange from="390" to="390" unit="page"/>
                                    <citedRange from="409" to="409" unit="page"/>
                                    <citedRange from="418" to="418"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p> The manuscript later belonged to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName> and is listed in its inventories and catalogues. Of the signa listed on <locus from="1r" to="2r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <quote>28</quote> is found in a catalogue from 1700 (U 91:2a); <quote>134</quote> in the inventory from 1720 (U 90:2, f. 9v) and <quote>136</quote> in the inventory from 1722 (U 90:3, p. 39). The current signa found on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> was first established in Helin’s catalogue from the 1720s (U 91:2:2).</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>From the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName> to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> in <date when="1780"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
